Ticket ID: SEC-INC-2025-09-PSH-01
Title: Cross-Device PowerShell Alert Investigation & Full Infrastructure Hardening
Classification: Security Incident Investigation / Infrastructure Hardening
Severity: Medium (No confirmed breach; treated as active threat)
Priority: High
Status: Closed – Hardened & Monitored
Incident Window: 1–14 September 2025
Affected Assets: Desktop II, Laptop II
Infrastructure Impacted: Home WiFi Router (Replaced)

Executive Summary
Between September 2–5, 2025, Windows Security flagged suspicious PowerShell activity on Desktop II and Laptop II within a 72-hour window. Alerts indicated possible fileless execution behavior, including:
	• Remote PowerShell exploitation attempts
	• Unauthorized script execution
	• Potential lateral movement
	• Configuration anomalies
Both systems shared the same WiFi router and similar OS/software baselines. No confirmed compromise was found, but a full incident response and zero-trust hardening was executed. All systems now operate under a hardened security baseline.
Business Impact
	• Risk Exposure: Remote execution, credential harvesting, lateral movement
	• Operational Impact: No downtime; remediation performed without service interruption
	• Security Improvements: Firewall reconstruction, legacy protocol removal, firmware validation, zero-trust outbound traffic enforcement

Incident Context
Trigger Event: Suspicious PowerShell execution alerts on two systems
Shared Risk Factors: Same router, similar Windows builds, similar application stacks
Initial Hypotheses:
	1. Remote PowerShell exploitation attempt
	2. Router-level exposure
	3. False positive from overlapping policy execution
	4. Malicious script execution attempt (fileless)
Escalation: Full precautionary response initiated

Incident Response Timeline
Date	Action
Sept 2	Alert on Desktop II
Sept 4–5	Alert on Laptop II
Sept 5–7	TRON remediation (both systems)
Sept 7–10	Firewall reconstruction
Sept 8–10	Router replacement
Sept 9–13	Credential & identity hardening
Sept 10–12	Firmware validation
Sept 14	Final verification & closure

Technical Findings
	• No malware binaries detected
	• No persistence via Scheduled Tasks
	• No malicious services or abnormal startup entries
	• No abnormal outbound traffic post-remediation
	• No firmware tampering indicators
	• No credential compromise confirmed

Remediation Summary
Phase 1 — TRON Multi-Stage Remediation
	• Executed tron.bat in Normal and Safe Mode
	• Debloat, malware removal, registry cleanup, temp file purge, DISM repair, SFC validation, Windows Update repair
	• Validation: sfc /scannow, DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /CheckHealth → No integrity violations
Phase 2 — Security Validation
	• Microsoft Defender full and offline scans
	• Manual review: Task Scheduler, services, startup entries, registry Run keys, PowerShell history
	• Network inspection: netstat -ano → No persistent suspicious activity
Phase 3 — Firewall Reconstruction (Zero Trust)
	• Default inbound/outbound deny
	• Blocked ports: RDP (3389), SMB (445), NetBIOS (139), RPC (135), SSDP (1900), LLMNR (5355)
	• Minimal outbound allow rules: HTTP (80), HTTPS (443), DNS (53 TCP/UDP)
Phase 4 — PowerShell & WinRM Hard Disable
	• Disable-PSRemoting -Force
	• WinRM service stopped and disabled
	• Listeners removed; firewall rules disabled
	• Validation: winrm quickconfig → Not configured
Phase 5 — Protocol & Legacy Service Removal
	• SMBv1 disabled
	• NetBIOS over TCP/IP disabled
	• UPnP services disabled
Phase 6 — DNS Hardening
	• Trusted DNS: 1.1.1.1 / 1.0.0.1 or 8.8.8.8 / 8.8.4.4
	• DNS cache flushed (ipconfig /flushdns)
Phase 7 — Router Replacement & Hardening
	• Physical replacement and firmware update
	• Admin credentials changed
	• Remote management disabled, UPnP/WPS disabled
	• WPA3 enabled, no port forwarding
Phase 8 — Firmware & Root-of-Trust Validation
	• BIOS reset and updated, Secure Boot enabled, TPM 2.0 verified
	• CSM disabled
	• CHIPSEC validation → SPI flash, BIOS write protections, UEFI integrity confirmed
Phase 9 — Credential Security Overhaul
	• Passwords rotated, unique policies enforced
	• Offline secure storage used
	• 2FA enabled
	• Authentication tokens reset

Validation & Verification
	• No recurring PowerShell alerts
	• No suspicious tasks, services, or outbound traffic
	• No firmware compromise detected
	• 7-day monitoring post-remediation → No incidents

Root Cause Analysis
	• Most Probable Cause: Configuration anomaly or benign PowerShell execution misclassified
	• Less Probable: Attempted but unsuccessful remote exploitation
	• Confirmed Compromise: None

Lessons Learned
	• Shared network infrastructure can amplify multi-device threat patterns
	• Default-allow outbound firewalls increase attack surface
	• Legacy protocols (SMBv1, NetBIOS, LLMNR) create unnecessary exposure
	• Firmware integrity validation should be included in remote-execution incident response

Long-Term Security Policy Implemented
	• Zero-trust firewall baseline (inbound/outbound)
	• Quarterly firmware validation
	• Periodic offline malware scans
	• Password rotation schedule
	• Router firmware review schedule
	• Controlled outbound traffic model
	• Legacy protocol removal standard

Final Status
	• Incident closed as precautionary
	• Systems operating under hardened baseline
	• No confirmed breach
	• Security posture significantly strengthened
